<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Tacitus</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> - 1st century Roman who is considered to be one of the more accurate historians of the ancient world.  In writing of the reign of Nero, he alludes to Christ's death as well as the existence of Christians in Rome. &quot;...the persons commonly called Christians, who were hated for their enormities.  Christus, the founder of their name, was put to death by Pontius Pilate...&quot; (<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Christus</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> - Latin for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Christ</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Lucian of Samosata</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> - Greek satirist of the latter half of the second century...he spoke scornfully of Christ and Christians, never assuming that they were unreal.<br>
<br>
The Gnostic source Gospel of Truth confirms that Jesus was a historical person in several of its passages.  <br>
<br>
The primary sources for the life of Christ are the four Gospels (which as I mentioned have been shown to be reliable).  However there are many other reports from non-Christian sources that supplement and confirm the Gospels.  (These are mostly from Greek, Roman, Jewish, and Samaritan sources of the 1st Century.)<br>
<br>
This link briefly covers a bit more...<br>
