But I have to say...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>I'm so happy</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->!</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  <br>
<br>
Before I started typing out my reply, I went digging on-line hoping to find the information that I had here on my bookshelf so I wouldn’t have to type it all out!  I found this debate transcript involving probably one of my favorite apologists.  It includes quite a bit of the info that I had here to post as well as what I would assume to be your rebuttal to my reply…let me know what you think.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.infidels.org/library/modern/farrell_till/geisler-till/index.shtml">www.infidels.org/library/...ndex.shtml</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
But, regarding your article on Paul, I have just a few things I wanted to pull out and comment on…<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>For example, the Persian sun-god Mithra, widely worshipped in the Roman Empire before the inception of the Christian era, had 12 disciples, performed miracles, was buried in a tomb, rose on the third day, was called the Good Shepherd, identified with the lamb, considered &quot;the Way, the Truth and the Light, the Redeemer, the Savior, the Messiah;&quot; his principal festival was held on what was to become Easter, and he instituted a Eucharist or Lord's Supper.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Regarding Mithraism, an honest reading of the NT info shows that Paul did not teach a new religion or draw on existing mythology.  A careful study of the Epistles and Gospels reveals that the source of Paul’s teachings on salvation was the OT and the teachings of Jesus.<br>
<br>
&quot;Allegations of an early Christian dependence on Mithraism have been rejected on many grounds. Mithraism had no concept of the death and resurrection of its god and no place for any concept of rebirth - at least during its early stages.... During the early stages of the cult, the notion of rebirth would have been foreign to its basic outlook.... Moreover, Mithraism was basically a military cult. Therefore, one must be skeptical about suggestions that it appealed to nonmilitary people like the early Christians.&quot; (Ronald Nash – Christianity and the Hellenistic World)<br>
<br>
Mithraism flowerd after Christianity, not before, so Christianity could not have copied from Mithraism.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The famous Golden Rule, which many associate with Jesus, was advocated by Confucius 500 years earlier and then later, long before the Gospels were concocted, by Hillel, a Pharisee (a member of an ancient Jewish sect). Hillel wrote: &quot;What thou dost not like, do thou not to thy neighbor. That is the whole; all the rest is explanation.&quot; One of Jesus' signature commandments--&quot;You shall love your neighbor as yourself&quot;--is cribbed verbatim from Leviticus 19:18 in the Old Testament.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Originality may or may not be a merit.  If the truth has already been uttered, the merit lies in repeating it, and giving it new and fuller appreciation.  The Golden Rule of the NT is a summing up of what everyone has always known to be right.  Great moral teachers never do introduce new moralities.  Their real job is to keep bringing us back, time and time again, to the old simple principles.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Paul with his epistles makes no mention of the events in the gospels so we can see he knew nothing of their content. He being the earliest writer (possibly as early as 30 CE) this would seem a powerful indictment of the gospels as written by eye-witness contemporaries fo JC.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
(Doesn’t he speak of the crucifixion? - 1 Cor. 15, I believe)<br>
<br>
Also, in Galatians, one can read that Paul’s message of the gospel was both checked and approved by the original apostles, demonstrating official recognition that his message was not opposed to that of Jesus.  The charge that Paul corrupted Jesus’ original message was long ago answered in The Origin of Paul’s Religion.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.markers.com/ink/jgmorigin.htm">www.markers.com/ink/jgmorigin.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Most if not all of the dating mentioned in your article differs considerably from the reference works that I’ve looked at, as you can see from the debate link above…but most liberal critics would like to place as much time as possible between when the events occurred and when they were written of.  <br>
<br>
Mr. Till (again, above link) dismisses the numerous copies of the manuscripts of the NT that we have as not being sufficient evidence…yet no one questions the other ancient historical copies of ancient literature.  It is only because we are dealing with the Bible.  <br>
<br>
I'm wanting to liken some of this to my great-grandmother’s bible that I have.  I can’t even tell you how old it is.  But it’s missing all of Genesis, half of Exodus, and half of Revelation (as well as the title page, record pages, etc…)  I’m seeing this as being the same thing.  Not a complete copy, yet I don’t doubt that it is an accurate copy.  The rest of it’s content has shown to be accurate and reliable as being a KJV bible, so why can’t I trust that it really is a KJV bible…but I feel as if I may be getting sidetracked…these subjects tie in together so easily….<br>
<br>
Help me to understand where you feel I err! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Candy<br>
